==English==

===Etymology===
From {{etyl|enm|en}}, from {{etyl|fro|en}} {{term|impetueux|lang=fro}}, from {{etyl|LL.|en}} {{m|la|impetuōsus||violent}}, from {{etyl|la|en}} {{term|impetus||attack||violence|lang=la}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|/imˈpɛtʃuəs/|lang=en}}
* {{audio|En-us-impetuous.ogg|Audio (US)|lang=en}}

===Adjective===
{{en-adj}}

# Making [[arbitrary]] decisions, especially in an impulsive and forceful manner.
#* '''1880''', John Weeks Moore, ''Complete Encyclopaedia of Music'', "[[s:Complete Encyclopaedia of Music/B/Beethoven, Louis Van|Beethoven, Louis Van ]]":
#*: But it was natural, that the '''impetuous''', restless young artist should incline more to excess of strength than of delicacy in his playing.
# Characterized by sudden and violent force.
#* '''1794''', [[w:Ann Radcliffe|Ann Radcliffe]], ''[[w:The Mysteries of Udolpho|The Mysteries of Udolpho]]'', vol. II, [[s:The Mysteries of Udolpho/Volume II/Chapter I|chapter I]]:
#*: He stands, and views in the faint rays<br>Far, far below, the torrent's rising surge,<br>And listens to the wild '''impetuous''' roar

